paragraphs.title: Inspired by Machine learning with Spark by Nick Pentreath
Notes about Eigenvectors and Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
paragraphs.text:
%md 
* Use eigenvectors to find the top (principal) components that describe the data
* Loosely described as the top classes/separations/decision boundaries of the data
* Reduces dimensions of data
* Can project original data into reduced-dimension space
* Components represent direction of eigenvector
* Explained variance is the magnitude
* Can't get back to actual feature from a component (limitation of PCA)
* Must standardize data on `mean` before performing eigenvalue decomposition

![Iris PCA Eigenvectors](http://advancedspark.com/img/iris-pca-eigenvectors.png)

paragraphs.title: Standardize/Scale The Input Pixel Vectors
paragraphs.text:
import org.apache.spark.mllib.feature.StandardScaler
import org.apache.spark.mllib.linalg.distributed.RowMatrix

val mllibStandardScaler = new StandardScaler(withMean=true, withStd=false)
  .fit(imagesAsPixelVectorsRDD)

val scaledImagesAsPixelRoxMatricesRDD = new RowMatrix(imagesAsPixelVectorsRDD.map(mllibStandardScaler.transform(_)))

%pyspark import matplotlib.pyplot as plt; plt.rcdefaults() import numpy as np import StringIO def show(p): img = StringIO.StringIO() p.savefig(img, format='svg') img.seek(0) print "%html
" + img.buf + "
" def plot_gallery(images, h, w, n_row=2, n_col=4): plt.clf() """Helper function to plot a gallery of portraits""" plt.figure(figsize=(1.8*n_col, 2.5*n_row)) plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0, left=0.01, right=0.99, top=0.90, hspace=0.35) for i in range(n_row * n_col): plt.subplot(n_row, n_col, i + 1) plt.imshow(images[:, i].reshape((h, w)), cmap=plt.cm.gray) plt.title("Eigenface %d" % (i + 1), size=12) plt.xticks(()) plt.yticks(())

paragraphs.title: Retrieve the PCA Matrix in Python
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

pdPcaMatrix = pd.read_csv("/tmp/eigenface/principal-components.csv", delimiter=",", header=0)
print(pdPcaMatrix.as_matrix)
